text: hi everyone calls any back Tano here the
internet's busiest music nerd and it's
time for a review of this new P.J Harvey
album I inside the old year dying this
is a brand new LP from one of the
underground's true vets and one of the
best singers and songwriters the 90s
ever had to offer us that is Miss PJ
Harvey with countless Classics under her
belt over the years one could say Harvey
has little to prove at this point and
could easily be feeding us a bunch of
rapidly released records that
essentially rehash the sounds of old
triumphs such as rid of me and to bring
you my love but instead she is still
locked deep into the current sound on
this leg of her career which began to
kick off years ago with some of the
eeriest releases in her catalog namely
2007's white chalk also the fiery and
socially conscious commentary throughout
let England Shake she also released
another album five years after that that
kind of paled in comparison to the
previous two the hopes 6 demolition
project which after that I'm not really
surprised that we saw her take a break
from commercially releasing music to
focus instead more on soundtrack work
and poetry which is kind of how things
snowballed into this new project here
that sees Harvey taking poems from her
recently released Orlan book and setting
them to music that often feels very
skeletal repetitive atmospheric with a
palette of very dark folk rock
instrumentation not too much unlike we
heard on England shake or hope six so a
similar itch is very much getting
scratched again but instrumentally and
melodically I guess you could say Harvey
is taking a simpler and more mesmerizing
approach which leaves us with moments
like Autumn term who's bare guitars and
drums I think could have used more
building out outside of course the
pianos that seep in around the midpoint
not to mention the vocal harmonies are
so cartoonishly ghoulish they kind of
render some of the Poetry a little
unintelligible anyway and structurally
the whole thing just Fizzles out in the
end even one of my favorite tracks on
this thing a child's question August
which features one of the gravest and
most beautiful choruses of Harvey's
career what says done
Love Me Tender Tender Love the
instrumental here really could have used
more variation outside of these distant
keys and some plotting drums that are
barely keeping pace and just feel like
they're about to fall asleep I mean
without a doubt for PJ Harvey this is a
somewhat odd album but sometimes I feel
like her in the band mistake these
instrumentals and raw noises for being
more experimental than they actually are
like with semini for example which I
think is one of the better tunes on this
project generally the doomy descending
chords are great the way the horns layer
up at a few parts of the cutter it's
Sinister but the track is also covered
with these random tremolo sound effects
that keep popping up in the background
like an annoying alarm or a phone
notification that won't stop I just
don't really see how it complements the
whole recording there's also the washed
out guitars and rhythmically grinding
Woody bits of percussion throughout
August another moment on the album where
I guess the music ends because the poem
itself just comes to a close which
really goes to show which part of PJ's
writing and creative process here is
kind of leading the way with these
tracks sometimes whatever instrumental
is in the background just kind of comes
across like a second thought A vibe I
also caught off the title track to this
thing which I wish was longer and it's
unfortunate because I do think there are
some good musical and Sonic ideas on
this project a lot of them just aren't
developed all that far like with the
Goosebump inducing vocals and cultist

again are all great but once we reach a

to continue building up from there and
slowly just Peters out like a cloud of
dust that at one point I could see but
the breeze just kind of takes it out of
the picture however it's not my
prerogative to totally tear This Record
apart there are certainly highlights the
closing track is quite fiery and
gratifying that's for sure inside the
old eye dying is also one of the better
Tunes here which was also a teaser to
the record ends with a very chilling and
repeated refrain and and I think this
track really brings home a lot of the
records themes around aging entering
into a different life phase some of what
PJ says on this track even goes as far
as to liken you know moving out of this
more youthful stage of her life to that
of shedding skin and look generally
speaking I do think the lyrics and
poetry throughout these tracks is very
good I especially liked what was written
into the track Lonesome Tonight a story
of a lost love that's told in very
evocative fragments with some surprising
Elvis references that come up at least
during a few points during the record
and that's one thing about these poems a
lot of them do kind of connect on a
deeper level and also on a macro level
as a story and while these characters
such as Elvis you know do have
references or illusions that you know
sort of tie into the real world that we
live in the way they operate in the
tales that Harvey is pulling together on
this record they come across almost like
otherworldly and folkloric in addition
to that I love the language that Harvey
uses on a lot of these cuts too there's
kind of an old world dialect to much of
it that are really kind of transports me
to whatever surreal fever dream
everything that's being written about
here is happening in but yeah overall I
did like this record and I thought it
was a pretty decent one for Harvey even
if there were some finer instrumental
details or inner workings that I think
could have been more interesting more
detailed or some of the song structures
just built out a bit more even with
those shortcomings the Tunes the
instrumentals the performances on this
thing are quite haunting quite gripping
even with them being as Ghostly and as
subtle as they are and I'm feeling a
light to decent seven on this one
